('computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays:learn:3bc2ded8', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays', '2.2.3b Arrays', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Finding the largest value in an array", "reading": "<h4>Keeping track of the biggest value seen so far</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>To find the largest element, start by assuming the <strong>first</strong> element is the largest, then compare every other element against it — updating whenever a bigger value is found.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">array temps[4]\ntemps[0] = 14\ntemps[1] = 21\ntemps[2] = 19\ntemps[3] = 25\nlargest = temps[0]\nfor i = 1 to 3\n  if temps[i] > largest then\n    largest = temps[i]\n  endif\nnext i\nprint(largest)    // 25</div>\n<ul>\n<li>The loop starts at <code>i = 1</code>, not 0 — <code>temps[0]</code> has already been used to set the starting value of <code>largest</code>.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "In the algorithm above, why does  largest  start as  temps[0]  before the loop even begins?", "options": ["Because temps[0] is guaranteed by the ERL specification to always automatically hold the biggest value in any array whatsoever", "So there is already a value to compare every other element against, without needing a separate ''no value yet'' case", "Because the loop is not permitted to begin running until at least one variable has already been given a value beforehand", "Because index 0 is defined to always hold the smallest possible value that any array element could ever store"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Starting largest as the first element gives the comparison loop something to compare against right from its very first pass — no special ''empty'' case is needed."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays:learn:10594c22', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays', '2.2.3b Arrays', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Searching an array for a value", "reading": "<h4>Checking every element for a match</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A <strong>linear search</strong> checks each element in turn against a target value, using a Boolean <strong>flag</strong> variable to record whether a match has been found.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">array codes[5]\ncodes[0] = 12\ncodes[1] = 47\ncodes[2] = 8\ncodes[3] = 47\ncodes[4] = 30\ntarget = 8\nfound = false\nfor i = 0 to 4\n  if codes[i] == target then\n    found = true\n  endif\nnext i\nprint(found)    // true</div>\n<ul>\n<li>The loop still checks <strong>every</strong> element, even after a match is found at index 2 — this simple linear search does not stop early.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "In the search above, what value is stored in  found  once the loop has finished?", "options": ["false, because target is compared against codes[4] last, and codes[4] does not equal 8, so found ends up false", "true, but only because codes[3] happens to equal 47, not because of the actual target value 8 being searched for", "true, because codes[2] equals the target value 8, and no line resets found back to false afterwards", "It cannot be determined, since found is never actually given a starting value before the loop begins running at all"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "codes[2] equals the target (8), so found is set to true on that pass — and nothing in the rest of the loop ever sets it back to false."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays:learn:4fa269f3', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays', '2.2.3b Arrays', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "2D arrays — a grid of rows and columns", "reading": "<h4>Storing table-shaped data</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A <strong>2D array</strong> stores data arranged as a <strong>grid</strong> — rows and columns — useful for anything table-shaped, such as a seating plan, a spreadsheet, or a game board.</li>\n<li>It is declared with <strong>two</strong> sizes: <code>array grid[3,4]</code> declares a grid with <strong>3 rows</strong> and <strong>4 columns</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">array grid[3,4]     // 3 rows, 4 columns — 12 elements in total</div>", "question": "How many elements does  array seatingPlan[4,5]  hold in total?", "options": ["9, because the two numbers in a 2D array''s declaration are added together rather than multiplied", "4, because only the first number in the declaration actually has any effect on a 2D array''s size", "5, because only the second number in the declaration actually has any effect on a 2D array''s size", "20"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "A 2D array''s total elements = rows × columns. seatingPlan[4,5] is 4 rows × 5 columns = 20 elements."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays:learn:4ff32c07', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays', '2.2.3b Arrays', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Accessing 2D array elements", "reading": "<h4>Two indices: row, then column</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>An element of a 2D array is accessed with <strong>two indices</strong> in square brackets, separated by a comma: <code>grid[row, col]</code>.</li>\n<li>Both indices are <strong>0-indexed</strong>, exactly like a 1D array — so <code>grid[0,0]</code> is the <strong>top-left</strong> cell of the grid.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">array grid[3,3]\ngrid[0,0] = \"X\"\ngrid[0,2] = \"O\"\ngrid[2,1] = \"X\"\nprint(grid[0,2])    // \"O\"\nprint(grid[2,1])    // \"X\"</div>", "question": "For  array grid[3,3] , which cell does  grid[0,2]  refer to?", "options": ["Row 0, column 2 — the last cell of the first (top) row", "Row 2, column 0 — the first cell of the last row, since the row is always written as whichever number comes second", "Column 0, row 2, because a 2D array''s two indices are always written column-first rather than row-first in ERL", "The centre cell of the grid, since index 2 always refers to the middle position of a 3-element row or column"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "grid[row, col] — grid[0,2] is row 0 (the top row) and column 2 (the last column of a 3-column row)."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays:learn:e770b389', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays', '2.2.3b Arrays', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Looping through a 2D array with nested loops", "reading": "<h4>A loop inside a loop — one for rows, one for columns</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>To visit <strong>every</strong> element of a 2D array, use <strong>nested loops</strong>: an <strong>outer</strong> loop for the row index, and an <strong>inner</strong> loop for the column index.</li>\n<li>For each single pass of the outer loop, the <strong>whole</strong> inner loop runs — moving across every column in that row before moving on to the next row.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">array grid[2,3]\ngrid[0,0] = 1\ngrid[0,1] = 2\ngrid[0,2] = 3\ngrid[1,0] = 4\ngrid[1,1] = 5\ngrid[1,2] = 6\ntotal = 0\nfor row = 0 to 1\n  for col = 0 to 2\n    total = total + grid[row, col]\n  next col\nnext row\nprint(total)    // 21</div>", "question": "In the nested loop above, how many times does the line  total = total + grid[row, col]  execute in total?", "options": ["2 times, because that is how many times the outer loop itself runs from start to finish, on its own", "6 times — once for every one of the 6 elements in the 2×3 grid", "3 times, because that is how many times the inner loop runs during just one single pass of the outer loop", "12 times, because the 2 rows must always be multiplied again by the number 2 once the columns have been counted"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Every pass of the outer loop (2 rows) runs the whole inner loop (3 columns), so the line runs 2 × 3 = 6 times — once per element."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays:misc:8260ef90', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays', '2.2.3b Arrays', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking array indices start at 1, matching everyday counting.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> ERL arrays are <strong>0-indexed</strong>: the first element is always at index <strong>0</strong>. For <code>array codes[4]</code>, the valid indices are <code>0, 1, 2, 3</code> — there is no <code>codes[4]</code>.</p>", "question": "array codes[4]  is declared. Which of these is NOT a valid index for this array?", "options": ["4", "0", "1", "2, because valid indices for an array are always counted down from its declared size, finishing at the number one"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A 4-element array has indices 0, 1, 2 and 3 (0-indexed) — index 4 does not exist, since the last valid index is always one less than the declared size."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays:misc:56de8b15', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays', '2.2.3b Arrays', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking an array can grow bigger while the program is running, simply by assigning a value beyond its declared size.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> ERL arrays are <strong>static</strong> — their size is fixed once declared. Assigning to an index beyond the declared size (e.g. <code>levels[3]</code> for a 3-element array with indices 0–2) causes an <strong>error</strong>, not automatic resizing.</p>", "question": "array levels[3]  is declared. What happens if the program tries to run  levels[3] = 10 ?", "options": ["It causes an error, because index 3 is out of range for a 3-element (0, 1, 2) static array", "The array automatically grows to hold 4 elements instead of 3, since ERL arrays resize themselves as needed", "levels[3] is simply ignored by the program, and the rest of the code afterwards runs completely normally", "The value 10 overwrites whatever was previously stored at levels[0], since index 3 wraps back around to the start"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "levels[3] is out of range for a 3-element array (valid indices 0, 1, 2) — since ERL arrays are static, this causes an error rather than growing the array."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays:misc:147e7db1', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays', '2.2.3b Arrays', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking the two numbers in a 2D array''s declaration, e.g. array grid[3,5], are added together rather than giving separate rows and columns.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The two numbers in a 2D declaration give the <strong>rows</strong> and the <strong>columns</strong> separately. The total number of elements is found by <strong>multiplying</strong> them, not adding them.</p>", "question": "array board[4,2]  is declared. How many elements does this hold in total, and how many rows does it have?", "options": ["8 elements in total, arranged as 4 rows of 2 columns each", "6 elements in total, since the two numbers in the declaration are added together rather than multiplied", "4 elements in total, because only the first number in a 2D declaration actually has any effect at all", "2 elements in total, because only the second number in a 2D declaration actually has any effect at all"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "board[4,2] is 4 rows × 2 columns = 8 elements in total — the two numbers are multiplied, not added."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays:misc:67cf9093', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays', '2.2.3b Arrays', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking grid[row, col] and grid[col, row] always refer to the same cell.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The <strong>order</strong> of the two indices matters: the first index is always the <strong>row</strong>, and the second is always the <strong>column</strong>. <code>grid[0,1]</code> and <code>grid[1,0]</code> are different cells unless the grid happens to be symmetrical at that point.</p>", "question": "For  array grid[3,3] , is  grid[0,1]  the same cell as  grid[1,0] ?", "options": ["No — grid[0,1] is row 0, column 1, while grid[1,0] is row 1, column 0; these are different cells unless the grid happens to be symmetrical", "Yes, because the order in which the two indices happen to be written down never actually makes the slightest difference at all for any 2D array in ERL", "Yes, but only because grid[3,3] happens to be a square grid with exactly the same number of rows as it has columns", "No, because grid[1,0] is not actually considered to be a valid reference into any 2D array whatsoever, under any circumstances"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "grid[row, col] — the row always comes first. grid[0,1] and grid[1,0] are two different cells unless their values happen to match."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays:misc:cb16066d', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays', '2.2.3b Arrays', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking a for loop over an array should run  for i = 0 to size , using the array''s declared size as the loop''s upper bound.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The loop''s upper bound should be <strong>(size − 1)</strong>, the array''s <strong>last valid index</strong> — not the declared size itself. For <code>array data[6]</code>, the correct loop is <code>for i = 0 to 5</code>.</p>", "question": "array data[6]  is declared. Which for loop correctly visits every element without going out of range?", "options": ["for i = 0 to 5", "for i = 0 to 6, because that matches the number used in the array''s own declaration", "for i = 1 to 6, since counting normally starts at one rather than at zero", "for i = 0 to 7, to make sure that every possible element is definitely included"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "data[6] holds indices 0 to 5 (0-indexed) — the loop''s upper bound should be (size − 1) = 5, not the declared size 6."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays:misc:e4bca6ec', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays', '2.2.3b Arrays', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking a simple linear search loop (with no explicit exit instruction) automatically stops checking as soon as it finds a match.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Unless the algorithm includes an explicit exit instruction, a plain <code>for</code> loop carries on running through <strong>every</strong> remaining index, even after a match has already been found earlier in the array.</p>", "question": "A linear search is written using a plain  for i = 0 to n-1  loop, with no exit statement. If the target is found at index 1 out of 5 elements, does the loop stop searching immediately at index 1?", "options": ["No — without an explicit exit instruction, the for loop carries on checking every remaining index up to the end", "Yes, because any linear search automatically stops as soon as the very first match is found, in every implementation", "Yes, because for loops in ERL always stop the moment any variable inside them changes value at all", "No, but only because index 1 does not count as a valid match for a search algorithm to actually stop on"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A plain for loop with no exit instruction always runs to completion — it keeps checking every remaining index, even once found has already been set to true."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays:tips:73687ec7', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays', '2.2.3b Arrays', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Tracing 1D and 2D array loops carefully", "reading": "<p>\"What does this output?\" questions on arrays are worth a lot of marks, and the safest approach is <strong>slow and mechanical</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>For a 1D array loop, draw a small table with a column for the <strong>index</strong> and a column for any <strong>running total</strong> (or other tracked variable), and fill it in one pass at a time.</li>\n<li>For a 2D array with nested loops, keep the <strong>row</strong> and <strong>column</strong> values in separate columns of your own working — it''s easy to mix them up under pressure.</li>\n<li>Remember that a loop bound written as <code>to (size − 1)</code>, e.g. <code>for i = 0 to 3</code> for a 4-element array, is <strong>correct</strong> — it is not \"missing\" the last element.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Example:</strong> for <code>nums = [3, 7, 2]</code> and <code>total = 0; for i = 0 to 2: total = total + nums[i]</code>, the table fills in i=0 (total 3), i=1 (total 10), i=2 (total 12). Output: 12. Slow beats clever.</p>", "question": "What is the safest way to answer a ''what does this array code output?'' question?", "options": ["Work through the loop mechanically, one pass (or one index) at a time, writing down each new value as it changes", "Read the code once quickly, then write down whichever final answer feels the most likely to you, based only on the variable names that have been used", "Only check the very last line of the algorithm, since the earlier lines only very rarely affect the value that ends up being printed", "Count how many lines the algorithm has in total, since the final output is usually equal to that same number of lines exactly"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Working through the loop mechanically — one pass or one index at a time — is reliable. Guessing from names or skipping lines is not."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays:tips:1fcfcf23', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays', '2.2.3b Arrays', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "explain — Writing a 1D array algorithm from a description (sum / largest / search)", "reading": "<p>When asked to <strong>write</strong> an array algorithm (rather than trace one), a reliable structure earns the marks reliably:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Declare</strong> the array with the correct size, and use a <code>for</code> loop running from <code>0</code> to <code>(size − 1)</code> to fill or read it.</li>\n<li>Before the main loop, set up any <strong>accumulator</strong> (e.g. <code>total = 0</code>) or starting value (e.g. <code>largest = arr[0]</code>) or <strong>flag</strong> (e.g. <code>found = false</code>) that the algorithm needs.</li>\n<li>Inside the loop, apply the correct comparison or calculation to <strong>each</strong> element in turn.</li>\n<li>After the loop finishes, <strong>output</strong> the final result.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Marks are usually given for the logic — correct array use, correct loop bounds, correct comparison/accumulation, and a correct output — not for using one particular programming language, so pseudocode or Python are both fine unless the question says otherwise.</p>", "question": "What is the best general approach when asked to WRITE an algorithm that processes an array?", "options": ["Skip straight to the comparison logic, since the array declaration and loop bounds are not usually worth any marks", "Declare the array with the right size, loop from 0 to (size − 1), and set up any accumulator or flag before the loop starts", "Write the whole algorithm using only a while loop, since for loops are never accepted by OCR mark schemes for any array question at all", "Always include a completely separate 2D array in the answer, even when the question itself only ever describes a single list of values"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "A reliable structure is: declare the array correctly, loop from 0 to (size − 1), set up any accumulator/flag before the loop, then output the result afterwards."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays:tips:dff80019', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays', '2.2.3b Arrays', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — 2D arrays — keep row and column straight", "reading": "<p>Mixing up the row and column index is one of the most common mistakes in 2D array questions. Some quick anchors:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>In <code>grid[row, col]</code>, the <strong>first</strong> value written is always the <strong>row</strong>, and the <strong>second</strong> is always the <strong>column</strong>.</li>\n<li><code>grid[0,0]</code> is the <strong>top-left</strong> cell — both indices start at 0, exactly like a 1D array.</li>\n<li>In nested loops, the convention is an <strong>outer</strong> loop for rows and an <strong>inner</strong> loop for columns — the inner loop runs fully for every single pass of the outer loop.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Why is the order of the two indices in  grid[row, col]  important?", "options": ["Because the second index written is always assumed to represent the row, not the column, in every 2D array", "Because ERL automatically swaps the two indices around whenever the array happens to have equal numbers of rows and columns", "Because grid[row, col] and grid[col, row] refer to different cells unless the row and column indices happen to be equal", "Because 2D arrays are not actually indexed from 0 in the same way that 1D arrays are indexed"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The order matters because the first index is always the row and the second is always the column — swapping them points to a different cell unless the two values happen to match."}'::jsonb),
